<TEXT>
legislation broadening the power of banks to 
enter the securities industry but narrowing their opportunities to 
offer insurance would offer a mixed bag to consumers of financial 
services 
the provisions are contained in a bill passed late wednesday by 
the senate banking committee the bill which must go before the 
full senate dismantles most of the barriers between commercial and 
investment banking in place since the depression 
supporters say businesses and state and local governments would 
pay lower underwriting fees because of added competition in the 
securities business they say individual investors would pay lower 
mutual fund fees for the same reason 
home buyers could save as much as 1000 on a 100000 mortgage 
says sen william proxmire dwis chairman of the committee and 
the bills sponsor 
consumer groups are also hailing a section sponsored by sen 
christopher dodd dconn that provides new safeguards on home 
equity loans 
but limits on bank involvement in insurance also sponsored by 
dodd could hamper competition in that field they say 
despite the lopsided 182 vote by the senate committee 
signaling almost certain passage in the full senate similar bills 
in the house face more uncertain prospects there jurisdiction 
over the issue is shared by the energy and commerce and the banking 
committees 
house banking committee chairman fernand j st germain dri 
has expressed great skepticism about allowing banks too many new 
powers 
rep edward j markey dmass chairman of the finance 
subcommittee of the energy and commerce committee has said he 
favors phasing in new powers for banks so federal regulatory 
agencies arent swamped 
it is essential that congress link the introduction of new 
powers to regulatory preparedness he said in a statement 
thursday 
the home equity loan section of the proxmire bill requires 
lenders to disclose the interest rate on loans in a clear and 
uniform manner as well as closing costs and repayment terms it 
also would prohibit lenders from unilaterally changing the terms of 
a home equity line of credit after the contract is signed 
michelle meier an attorney for the consumers union and leslie 
gainer of us pirg a group associated with consumer activist 
ralph nader said in a statement that the proxmire version is an 
improvement over a similar home equity bill in the house which 
does not bar unilateral changes 
another section would make it easier for consumers to shop for a 
place to put their money by requiring banks and mutual funds to 
advertise in a uniform manner the interest rate paid on deposits 
and money market accounts 
under the bill banks would get immediate power to underwrite 
mortgagebacked securities commercial paper and municipal revenue 
bonds 
they would be able to deal in mutual funds and corporate bonds 
six months after enactment but in a concession to the securities 
industry banks would not be allowed to underwrite corporate stock 
viewed by senators as the riskiest securities area unless 
congress authorizes that in a separate vote early in 1991 
on insurance the bill permits state officials to authorize 
statechartered banks and bank holding companies to underwrite 
insurance within their home states but they will not be able to 
sell insurance outside their home state and the bill would close 
loopholes that permit some national banks to sell insurance 
</TEXT>
