two large holes opened up in a road in 
eastern england swallowing a doubledecker bus and prompting the 
evacuation of a small hotel and nearby homes police said 
authorities believe the road near the city of norwich was built 
above an abandoned 19th century chalk mine 
one hole opened under the rear of the bus thursday and the 
driver ordered the 20 passengers off the vehicle immediately the 
british broadcasting corp reported but as the driver tried to 
pull away the hole grew into a 26footwide gap and another hole 
appeared nearby 
the television report showed the bus with its rear in the hole 
and its front wheels in the air 
chief inspector david cushing of norwich police said city 
authorities ordered the evacuation of the hotel and nearby homes as 
the holes grew larger underground gas electricitry and domestic 
water supplies were disrupted 
the evacuated people spent the night at a school as workmen 
attempted repairs 
