reaching large numbers of voters 
as the approaching super tuesday primaries strain campaign 
warchests and candidate schedules satellite uplinking is being 
used by presidential hopefuls to increase their exposure to voters 
in the cheapest way possible 
though many stations refuse these brief interview opportunities 
the chance for live time with the candidates has become 
attractive to smaller stations in areas where the contenders are 
not likely to appear in person 
but some media experts say the new hightech tool of the 1988 
campaign does not serve the public well 
it plays on the vanity of the local media because everyone 
wants to be seen interviewing a presidential candidate but the 
tough questions arent being asked by the local interviewers 
said kathleen hall jamieson a communications professor at the 
university of texas at austin 
the candidates wont run into any sam donaldsons in the 132nd 
market said stephen hess senior fellow at the washington 
dcbased brookings institution referring to abcs tough 
sometimes abrasive white house correspondent 
costs for transmitting via satellite vary depending on location 
and equipment used but generally it is far less expensive than 
producing and airing an advertisement 
airing a 30second ad on a boston television station during the 
popular cosby show program can cost 30000 while buying 90 
minutes of satellite time that can be used for fiveminute 
interviews by 18 stations costs about 2000 said gary galanis a 
spokesman for democrat paul simons campaign 
we at this point dont have the resources to buy even a 
minimum amount of paid advertising which would probably be about a 
million dollars to hit all the super tuesday states galanis said 
you cant mold your message as well with satellite interviews 
but you can get two to three minutes on a local newscast he 
said paid advertising is the best thing but the next best 
thing is satellite uplinks 
tim archie a spokesman for republican bob dole said large 
stations in major markets are less likely to accept a satellite 
interview because they are in cities where the candidates are 
appearing anyway these stations also often have a reporter on the 
road with the campaigns 
but for other stations satellite interviews give the stations 
a sense of an exclusive he said 
