<TEXT>
a number of democratic congressmen want the 
final totals of the 1990 national census adjusted to make up for 
the many minority group members and city dwellers they say will be 
overlooked 
commerce department and census officials who have refused to 
agree to such changes were criticized thursday at a hearing for 
making shameful and political decisions 
every census since 1790 has seen at least some criticism for the 
socalled undercount and the complaints have grown in recent 
years despite improvements in census taking 
officials estimate that in 1980 only about 1 percent of 
americans were missed in the national head count but they admit 
the problem was much greater among minorities and in cities than it 
was for other groups 
studies were launched to try and determine if adjustments could 
be made to compensate for this problem but last october the 
decision was announced that there would be no adjustment in 1990 
pointing out that the people usually missed are most often 
minorities and city residents where the democratic party 
predominates rep charles schumer of new york termed the decision 
not to adjust shameful and political 
he said the action was not based on fairminded concern about 
accurate statistics its a raw exercise of partisan politics 
schumers remarks came thursday at a hearing of the house post 
office and civil service census subcommittee reps mervyn m 
dymally of california and robert garcia of new york also raised 
concerns about the decision not to adjust all three are democrats 
commerce undersecretary robert ortner denied that politics were 
involved in the decision contending that statisticians disagree on 
whether there is an accurate method of making adjustments 
i dont think it would make the problem any better if we were 
to devise an elaborate mathematical system to make up new 
numbers ortner said 
the focus of the problem is the fact that all 435 seats in the 
house of representatives and billions of dollars in state and 
federal money are distributed on the basis of the figures collected 
every 10 years by the census bureau 
</TEXT>
