<TEXT>
a 50yearold law exempting truck and bus 
drivers in cities from meeting federal safety requirements is one 
step closer to being removed from the books 
the senate passed legislation thursday that would apply federal 
safety regulations within urban areas for the first time and would 
also commence government consideration of whether to put devices in 
trucks that would monitor drivers performances 
the bill which would also require the government to study how 
to improve truck braking systems was approved by a unanimous voice 
vote 
it is aimed at truck and bus accidents that kill more than 5000 
americans every year 
federal regulations set minimum standards for the construction 
and operation of trucks and buses and for the physical condition 
of their drivers they are often stricter and more detailed than 
state requirements 
but the rules do not apply in urban areas the regulations were 
written in the 1930s when urban traffic was slower than it is 
today and lawmakers believed city authorities could keep track of 
local problems 
the exemption for vehicles operating in cities would be 
eliminated one year after the bill becomes law 
the measure would also give the department of transportation a 
year to determine whether drivers performances must be monitored 
by instruments installed in the trucks and if so which devices 
should be used 
federal rules forbid commercial drivers from driving more than 
10 consecutive hours or 60 hours per week drivers are required to 
keep written records of their hours but these logs are believed to 
be frequently falsified 
mechanical and electronic devices are available that could 
record the driving time and speed of drivers 
the legislation would also give the transportation department 
until sept 30 to conduct a study on ways to improve truck braking 
systems and until a year after that to require better brakes if 
they are found to be necessary brake problems are believed to be a 
cause of up to onethird of all truck accidents 
the measures chief sponsors are sens john danforth rmo and 
brock adams dwash 
a similar bill is awaiting action in the house public works and 
transportation committee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

