<DOCNO> AP880304-0066 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the reagan administration has suspended new 
regulations that would have cut off federal funds to family 
planning clinics which offer abortions or abortion counseling 
after a judge ruled the guidelines were unconstitutional 
abortion referral and abortion counseling are constitutionally 
protected speech under the first amendment said us district 
judge walter j skinner issuing a permanent injunction thursday 
against enforcement of the regulations 
denying an otherwise eligible organization a grant because it 
provides abortion counseling or referral even with nonfederal 
funds constitutes an impermissable penalty for the exercise of a 
constitutionally protected right he said 
the regulations are specifically designed to suppress speech 
and particularly directed at the suppression of one viewpoint 
skinner said as a result they run directly contrary to the 
dictates of the first amendment 
he said the regulations also were contrary to the intent of 
congress when it established the family planning program under 
title x of the public health service act of 1970 
the regulations scheduled to take effect thursday will not be 
enforced while the administration reviews the ruling and decides 
whether to appeal said lucy eddinger a spokeswoman for the 
department of health and human services 
skinner ruled the guidelines would cause irreparable harm to 
women who receive services from the clinics and violate a womans 
right to privacy and to choose to have an abortion 
federal judges in denver and new york city had issued temporary 
injunctions against the new rules but had not ruled on their 
constitutionality and it was not clear whether those rulings had 
full nationwide force 
this court has national jurisdiction in federal question 
cases skinner saidin his 28page ruling 
the regulations had not been expected to affect the estimated 
4000 family planning clinics operated with federal funds because 
the rules apply only to new grants about 5 million poor women 
receive services through the clinics 
the injunction was requested last month by the state of 
massachusetts the national family planning and reproductive health 
association and 13 other local and national family planning groups 
although the injunction applied only to those clinics 
represented by the groups skinner said he expected secretary of 
health and human services otis r bowen to scrap the regulations 
scott r sterling executive director of the washington 
dcbased family planning association said he expected the 
administration to appeal because of political pressure 
we expect to be successful at the appeals level as well 
sterling said 
massachusetts attorney general james shannon called the ruling 
a major victory for a womans right to consult privately with her 
doctor 
the new rules would have prohibited federally funded family 
planning programs from providing abortion counseling referring 
women to abortion providers and engaging in lobbying or legal 
action to increase availability of abortions 
if the facility also performs abortions to keep title x funding 
for its other programs the clinic would have to maintain completely 
separate facilities for each type of patient 
in its attempt to implement a health care policy which 
promotes childbirth the defendant has devised a system which rests 
in large part of keeping title x clients in ignorance skinner 
said 
the title x budget for fiscal 1988 is 137 million down from 
142 million in fiscal 1987 
</TEXT>
