panama 
but the committee took no action on legislation introduced on 
thursday and cosponsored by 25 senators which would impose a total 
trade embargo on panama in an effort to break noriegas hold on the 
country 
the 150 committee vote approving the nonbinding resolution 
came after administration officials seeking to avoid passage of 
trade embargo legislation proposed a set of milder alternatives 
that still would penalize the noriega regime 
national security adviser colin powell told reporters thursday 
night that several economic and financial measures were being 
prepared for consideration by president reagan but he refused to 
be more specific 
other officials insisting on anonymity said the administration 
believes a bipartisan congressional proposal for a trade air 
travel and currency embargo against panama would be unwise 
the administration believes us interests would be better 
served if noriega were ousted primarily by panamanian and not 
american pressure 
the officials said displays of american heavyhandedness could 
be used by noriega to his advantage and could produce resentment 
elsewhere in latin america where us intervention has long been a 
popular antiamerican rallying cry 
the committee resolution declares that eric arturo devalle who 
was ousted by the panamanian parliament after trying to fire 
noriega as commander of panamas armed forces remains the 
countrys legitimate head of state and should reeceive the full 
moral political and diplomatic support of the government of the 
united states 
it called on the white house to formally terminate any and all 
contacts with gen noriega 
the government of the united states should consider further 
measures to support democracy in panama including economic 
sanctions in the event gen noriega continues to defy president 
devalles lawful order the resolution declared 
it also called on the white house to study the impact on us 
energy supplies if noriega reacts to possible economic sanctions by 
shutting down the transpanama petroleum pipeline used to transport 
alaskan oil to the east coast of the united states 
for noriega panamanian independence from the united states has 
been his principal line of defense in his struggle to survive it 
was a recurring theme at a progovernment demonstration in panama 
earlier this week when a crowd of 3000 turned out to cheer noriega 
shortly before powell made his comments to reporters while 
returning with reagan from the nato summit in brussels belgium 
six republicans and democrats introduced the embargo bill 
it would prohibit all trade and air travel between the two 
countries and bar us banks from transferring any funds to panama 
and its banking system 
by stopping the transfer of funds from us banks to panama 
we go for the jugular said sen alfonse damato rny a 
principal sponsor of the embargo plan 
because of panamas heavy reliance on its economic ties with 
the united states the impact of a us trade embargo would be 
immediate dramatic and devastating to noriega and his cohorts 
damato said 
a ban on panamanian goods would paralyze a 412 million market 
representing 60 percent of panamas total exports damato said a 
ban on us exports to panama would affect a 30 percent slice of 
all panamanian imports he said 
other sponsors of the embargo bill are sens edward m kennedy 
dmass david durenberger rminn bob graham dfla john 
kerry dmass and jesse helms rnc 
the administration has been sending mixed signals about the 
degree to which it is willing to pressure noriega who is under 
federal indictment on drug smuggling charges and who forced out the 
constitutionally elected president last week 
some officials are sensitive to charges that the administration 
has not done enough to oppose noriega while others believe broader 
us interests require a cautious approach 
in any case there appears to be a consensus within the 
administration that a trade embargo is too ambitious a step the 
administration is hopeful a combination of other pressures will 
force an end to noriegas rule 
the issue of whether to withhold a 7 million us payment due 
in midmarch to panama for canalrelated fees and services has 
underscored the split in the administration 
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams has said that the 
administration will refuse to deliver the funds if such a request 
is received from ousted president eric arturo delvalle 
but on thursday state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley 
said no final decision has been made on that issue even though the 
administration has had the request in hand since earlier in the 
week 
she acknowledged however that the request probably will be 
honored 
with an assist from the administration panamanian authorities 
apparently have been denied access to official funds on deposit in 
us banks 
at a news conference thursday night at the panamanian embassy 
an attorney for delvalle said federal courts in new york and boston 
have issued temporary restraining orders to prevent withdrawal of 
the funds 
we believe that whatever funds are in those institutions are 
at this point frozen and cannot be transmitted to the noriega 
regime said daniel resnick a washington attorney 
</TEXT>
