<TEXT>
geneticist sewall wright known for his 
pioneering studies of genetic changes in evolving species died of 
complications resulting from injuries sustained in a fall he was 
98 
wright a professor emeritus at the university of 
wisconsinmadison remained active until his death thursday he 
published his last scientific paper in the january 1988 issue of 
american naturalist 
he broke his pelvis sunday when he slipped on an ice patch while 
walking near his apartment 
wright advocated a mathematical theory of evolution one of his 
important theories was that chance happenings can have a 
significant effect on modifying the gene pool 
wright received 10 honorary degrees and was awarded the darwin 
medal the national medal of science and in 1984 the 100000 
balzan prize 
he was one of the great thinkers in all of genetics and 
evolution said james crow a university of wisconsin colleague 
and longtime friend 
he was responsible along with ra fisher and jsb haldane 
for our modern theory of evolution selection and mendelian 
inheritance 
wright who was born in melrose mass was a faculty member at 
the university of chicago for 30 years until 1954 when he retired 
from that school he then accepted a position at uwmadison where 
he has been emeritus professor of genetics since 1960 
wright is survived by two sons and a daughter 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

