<TEXT>
contra rebels kidnapped 13 people in 
northern nicaragua including an american volunteer for the witness 
for peace organization its local director said today 
edward griffin the local director for the organization 
identified the kidnapped american as richard boren 29 of elkin 
nc 
organization officials said boren was a witness for peace 
volunteer in the jinotega province of nicaragua and had been 
documenting contra activities including human rights abuses 
witness for peace opposes the contras and the reagan 
administrations policies in central america 
griffin said boren was abducted tuesday in the mancotal area of 
jinotega province about 120 miles north of managua it is a zone 
where the rebels operate regularly in their sixyear fight against 
the sandinista government 
a defense ministry communique said two contras and four 
defenders of the resettlement village were killed in the attack it 
said the contras leader identified only as wilmer was one of the 
dead rebels 
in washington contra spokesman bosco matamoros denied that the 
group had been kidnapped saying they were detained by rebel 
forces who suspected them of being foreign military collaborators 
with the sandinistas 
matamoros said the 13 will be released as soon as a 
trustworthy nicaraguan can be found to return them to a safe 
location 
generally kidnapped civilians are held for a few days by the 
contras and then released 
matamoros accused the sandinista government of sending 
foreigners especially americans to war zones its purpose is to 
put them into a dangerous situation he said 
witness for peace said boren had been in nicaragua since 
november documenting contra human rights abuses and leading 
delegations to areas of conflict 
the groups statement said boren was a selfemployed 
construction worker and had worked for three years with the peace 
corps in ecuador before coming to nicaragua 
last october another witness for peace volunteer paul fisher 
was kidnapped and held for 14 days by the contras 
in washington witness for peace said it had contacted the us 
state department and the us embassy in managua the state 
department had no immediate confirmation 
dennis marker the organizations washington director said two 
witness for peace volunteers in jinotega were going today into the 
area where boren was taken to get more details on the incident 
marker said witness for peace has no connection with the 
nicaraguan government and documents abuses by the sandinistas and 
contras although our experience in the last four years is that 
the large majority of abuses are contra abuses 
he said witness for peace has 32 fulltime volunteers in 
nicaragua the group also sponsors tours to rural nicaragua every 
two weeks for americans interested in the contra issue 
