<TEXT>
israel blocked journalists from major trouble 
spots in the occupied territories friday in an effort to limit news 
reports of explosive palestinian protests following weekly moslem 
prayers 
the media clampdown came after complaints from politicians 
soldiers and settlers that the presence of journalists often 
inflamed arab protests in the west bank and gaza and caused more 
violence 
despite the absence of cameras and notepads palestinian revolts 
occurred friday in most of the west banks major cities 
friday also marked the first time since the start of arab unrest 
on dec 8 that israeli soldiers had blocked major roads and turned 
back journalists from cities and refugee camps that typically are 
the sites of postprayer protests 
brig gen ephraim lapid the armys spokesman in tel aviv told 
the associated press the barricades did not represent an official 
change in military policy 
there are a few localities that are closed according to 
existing policy which allows local commanders to shut an area based 
on operational needs lapid said 
the army declined to say how many cities and refugee camps were 
offlimits to journalists but in the west bank soldiers barred 
reporters from more than half a dozen major cities only bethlehem 
the traditional birthplace of jesus was open 
this is a closed military area one soldier told an ap 
photographer outside nablus 40 miles north of jerusalem if you 
dont leave now we will arrest you 
an army jeep then followed the photographers car for about 
three miles apparently to make sure it was headed toward jerusalem 
journalists were permitted to enter the gaza strip but kept 
from the area around gaza citys main mosque and the major 
commercial street 
the decision to bar journalists from the occupied territories 
drew mixed reviews from israelis 
the right to see bangbang is not protected by the first 
amendment said zeev chafets a former director of the government 
press office and a native of pontiac mich 
i would support closing off the west bank to the world press 
in a minute but keeping it open to the israeli press chafets 
said in an interview the world press is only an asterisk here 
to me whats important is my press 
but israel peleg also a former director of the government press 
office disagreed 
it is better to let the media operate freely and without any 
obstacles than to be depicted in the world as a country that 
restricts journalists peleg told the ap 
israels image may be immediately harmed by these pictures of 
protests but in the long run the fact that these pictures can be 
circulated speaks for israels democracy he said 
prime minister yitzhak shamir of the rightwing likud bloc twice 
this week publicly referred to the possibility of restricting media 
access and accused journalists of bias against israel 
some soldiers serving in the west bank also have said 
journalists make their jobs more difficult angry settlers in 
hebron attacked foreign photographers thursday accusing them of 
impeding troops efforts to arrest an arab who stabbed a 
15yearold settler 
four soldiers were arrested after a cbs news crew photographed 
them beating palestinians with rocks last week 
but foreign minister shimon peres of the leftleaning labor 
party has warned that barring media access to the occupied 
territories will simply spark rumors of atrocities that journalists 
will be unable to refute from onthescene reporting 
other israeli officials have warned that denying media access 
could lead to unfavorable comparisons between israel and south 
africa which the government has been sensitive about 
in south africa police can declare areas offlimits to 
journalists on the spot and demand that all reporters leave in 
israel local commanders also are permitted to declare an area 
closed if they deem the presence of journalists will make the 
armys job more difficult 
in addition to limiting access israel has military censors who 
in an effort to prevent what they consider to be incitement 
carefully control arabiclanguage newspapers based in jerusalem 
which circulate in the occupied territories 
but the censorship controls on foreign press coverage of the 
occupied territories have been less stringent 
robert slater chairman of the foreign press association said 
he was appalled but not surprised by israels decision to bar 
journalists from large portions of the territories friday 
from the prime ministers statements and comments by cabinet 
members it appeared increasingly likely the government would do 
something to keep us away from this story slater said in an 
interview we have fought it for three months and we will 
continue to fight it 
</TEXT>
