<TEXT>
the vast majority of americans view ties with 
europe as very important for the united states but at the same 
time they recognize that transatlantic links have waned over the 
past 10 years a poll commissioned by the european economic 
community shows 
the gallup poll of national opinion leaders and the general 
public published in the march edition of the eec magazine 
europe also shows the majority of respondents believe us 
troops must be stationed in europe to prevent a soviet attack 
of those polled 86 percent said us ties with europe matter 
a great deal compared with 65 percent who answered the same way 
in a 1973 poll commissioned by the magazine 
asked how todays ties compare with those of 10 years ago 33 
percent of the respondents said they were closer but 53 percent 
said they were not as close 
the united states should strengthen its links with europe 
according to 53 percent of those polled thirtyone percent favor 
the level of current ties and 11 percent support reduced ties with 
the continent 
although about onethird of the respondents said west european 
countries engage in unfair trading practices both the general 
public and national opinion leaders which the magazine defined as 
business and academic leaders and policy makers cited japan as an 
unfair trading partner more than twice as often as the countries of 
western europe 
for example 30 percent of the public said they view europe as 
an unfair partner while 65 percent cited japan 
respondents are more likely to know about the us trade deficit 
with japan than about the one with western europe according to the 
poll the 1987 deficit with japan was 598 billion the largest 
chunk of the 1712 billion overall deficit while the deficit 
with europe was 302 billion 
of those polled 47 percent said they mostly agree that 
europe is a good market for the united states while 31 percent 
said they completely agree 
those polled generally said they respect european achievements 
in arts but gave higher credit to us achievements in science 
encouragement of individual creativity and equal opportunity 
among the general public 54 percent said the united states 
provides an excellent education for its citizens while 21 percent 
said europe has a good educational system but among the opinion 
leaders 33 percent said the united states provides an excellent 
education and 34 percent credited europe with the same service 
the poll conducted late last year by telephone surveyed 1300 
adult americans and 387 opinion leaders the poll results had a 3 
percentage point margin of error 
