<TEXT>
president reagans fiscal 1989 budget would 
produce a deficit of 165 billion a congressional report said 
friday an amount that would trigger massive automatic spending 
cuts under the grammrudman law 
the deficit estimate by the congressional budget office is 30 
billion higher than the amount of red ink the white house office of 
management and budget says the presidents spending plan would 
create 
the differences are mainly because cbo is more pessimistic about 
the how the economy will perform than the administration is 
the grammrudman balanced budget law calls for a 136 billion 
deficit target in fiscal 1989 which begins oct 1 if final 
figures indicate the deficit will exceed that amount by more than 
10 billion domestic and defense spending would be slashed 
automatically by whatever amount it takes to shrink the deficit to 
136 billion 
the final deficit estimate however is made by omb with cbo 
playing only an advisory role according to omb reagans 11 
trillion budget would leave 130 billion in red ink and no 
automatic cuts would occur 
some lawmakers have expressed concern about the pessimistic 
economic and deficit forecasts that cbo has made this year but 
with 1988 an election year congress is not expected to seriously 
challenge ombs numbers and commence a painful round of spending 
cuts and tax increases 
acting cbo director james l blum who presented the report to 
the senate appropriations committee told the legislators that 
deciding which set of forecasts to trust is a political judgment 
call for them to make 
cbo expects slower economic growth and higher inflation and 
interest rates in the next two years than the administration does 
all of those factors would produce higher government spending and 
lower revenue collections than the white house anticipates 
blum conceded that recent economic statistics have been better 
than expected 
it would appear that the pronounced slowdown we were expecting 
in the first quarter of 1988 is not materializing he said 
cbo is also more pessimistic than the administration about 
longerrange efforts to reduce the deficit while the white house 
says the deficit will drop to 104 billion in 1990 and 23 billion 
by 1993 the congressional agency says the deficit will be 157 
billion in 1990 and 109 billion in 1993 
grammrudman requires a balanced budget by 1993 
the house and senate budget committees are expected to begin 
writing their own versions of the 1989 budget soon but neither is 
expected to propose any budgetcutting much beyond that proposed in 
the presidents plan reagans spending blueprint adheres closely 
to the socalled budget summit agreement he reached with 
congressional leaders last november 
among its projections cbo said 
the economy will grow by 18 percent this year compared with 
the administrations estimate of 24 percent 
inflation will be 49 percent in 1988 contrasted with a white 
house forecast of 43 percent 
enactment of reagans entire budget would reduce the deficit by 
12 billion below what it would be if no further deficitreduction 
action were taken 
