<TEXT>
the governments planned sale of the electricity 
industry in england and wales is by far the biggest and most 
controversial venture so far in prime minister margaret thatchers 
huge privatization program 
critics predict poorer service and higher prices and question 
the wisdom of putting nuclear power stations in private hands 
supporters insist it will produce better service with 
safeguards built on the lessons of past privatizations 
but investors weighing this debate also harbor big financial 
concerns in the wake of octobers stock market crash britons 
burned by the selloffs of british gas plc and british 
telecommunications plc shares understandably are wary of buying 
into another public utility 
the stock offering of the electric company now a state body 
run by the central electricity generating board is to be debated 
march 7 in parliament and the energy department already is taking 
steps to fend off criticism 
privatizing the electricity industry has been likened to 
trying to grasp a porcupine the sunday times commented 
the complex sale will take two to three years and could raise 
more money than the entire 165 billion pounds or about 29 
billion raised from all the other stateowned companies sold since 
mrs thatchers conservatives were elected in 1979 promising to 
roll back socialism in britain 
the city londons financial district expects the electricity 
sale to raise from 26 billion to 47 billion 
less controversial have been the sales of nonutility companies 
such as british airways plc and rollsroyce plc the airplane 
engine maker 
mrs thatchers goal has been to make these companies more 
competitive and to get more britons to become shareholders the 
shareowning public has tripled to 85 million in 10 years the 
government says 
the objections have been to the privatization of monopolies 
intact without the intention of introducing competition said 
dieter helm a research fellow at the london business school 
critics also complain that british gas and british telecom were 
insufficiently regulated when they went private in 1986 and 1984 
respectively consequently they claim gas and telephone prices 
have risen while service has deteriorated 
some britons also say they feel less secure without government 
control over such vital public services in the electricity sale 
critics fear higher prices deteriorating service and poor security 
for nuclear stations labor unions fear job losses 
helm said there also were questions over whether the capital 
markets could absorb all the stock to be sold 
moreover he said nuclear disasters in recent years at three 
mile island in the united states and at the chernobyl plant in the 
soviet union increase uncertainty about whether people really 
want to hold shares in this kind of firm 
the sale is opposed by lord marshall chairman of the central 
electricity generating board who says the plan is unlikely to 
serve the consumers interests 
lawmaker john prescott of the opposition labor party attacked 
the plan as a triumph of ideology over common sense and 
accused the government of selling off assets to finance tax cuts 
the government structured the sale defensively addressing some 
of the issues raised by the gas and phone selloffs it set up two 
competing generating companies and promised to implement regulation 
that will protect britains security and consumers rights 
for example energy secretary cecil parkinson plans rebates for 
dissatisfied consumers a privilege not granted to british telecom 
users 
tony boorman deputy director of the watchdog electricity 
consumers council called regulatory safeguards a welcome 
change 
weve always believed that at least in the short term the 
structure of the industry has less relevance to the customer than 
the regulation he said 
</TEXT>
