<TEXT>
a flight attendants union official said today 
that transportation department plans to test airline crews and 
ground workers for drug use would be unfair and unnecessary 
but transportation secretary james burnley defended the proposal 
announced thursday saying he did not want to wait until hundreds 
of people are killed before taking action to stop any potential 
problem 
vicky francovich president of the independent federation of 
flight attendants said that in the 50year history of the 
industry there have been no accidents blamed on employee drug use 
ms francovich interviewed with burnley on abctvs good 
morning america said the department should be looking for ways 
to combat fatigue among overworked airline personnel and to tighten 
certification procedures 
i think there are more responsible ways to deal with the 
problems she said adding that false positive drug tests could 
lead to an unfair stigma against an employee 
while the government is not dealing with problems in the 
deregulated industry it is attacking a problem here that 
doesnt really exist she said this is not a necessary 
approach 
burnley acknowledged that no airline accidents have been traced 
to drug use but he cited a pittsburgh press survey showing that 
six hospital emergency rooms had treated 23 cockpit crew members or 
flight attendants for drug overdoses 
burnley who was also interviewed on cbs this morning said 
one airline reported that 16 percent of job applicants for 
mechanics jobs were found to be using drugs and at another 
airline 6 percent of flight attendant applicants were drug users 
he did not name the airlines 
there is nothing beyond that anecdotal evidence that would 
indicate that the airline industry is somehow exempt from this 
problem that is plaguing all of american society so i think its 
pretty clear that we need to move in this area he said 
burnley said he expects a final rule to be implemented before 
the end of the year despite several pending court challenges to 
mandatory drug testing 
testing would cover the more than half a million commercial 
aviation employees who hold safetysenstive jobs from pilots and 
flight attendants to mechanics and security workers at airport 
checkpoints 
a fact sheet provided by the department suggested as many as 75 
percent of the 511000 workers who would be subject to the tests 
might show evidence of drug use but burnley sought to distance 
himself from the estimate saying it was included only as a means 
of roughly estimating the possible cost of such a program and not 
meant to indicate the extent of drug use in the industry 
the pilots and otherairline unions promised to challenge any 
random drug testing rule in court once it is made final drug 
testing already is the subject of numerous lawsuits and several 
federal courts of appeal have either upheld testing or knocked it 
down 
we cant wait for weeks and months while these drug testing 
cases wind themselves through the courts burnley said 
in addition to pilots and flight attendants the testing 
requirements would cover aircraft mechanics other cockpit crew 
member such as flight engineers and navigators aircraft 
dispatchers and security personnel who work at screening 
checkpoints at airports 
under the proposal employees would be subject to a 
preemployment test periodic testing whenever a person is taking a 
physical postaccident testing and random testing as well as test 
for reasonable cause an employee would be subject to an initial 
test on a sample of urine and a more sophisticated test if the 
first test shows the presence of drugs 
</TEXT>
