<TEXT>
japan posted an unadjusted current account surplus 
of 352 billion in january down 274 percent from 484 billion a 
year earlier the finance ministry said friday 
januarys surplus in the broadest measure of trade was also down 
from 944 billion in december said finance ministry official 
toshio naito the current account includes services and investment 
income as well as merchandise trade 
when adjusted for seasonal fluctuations the current account 
surplus for january stood at 803 billion down from 871 billion 
a year earlier but up from an adjusted 747 billion in december 
japans seasonally adjusted trade surplus in january fell 196 
percent from its level a year earlier marking the seventh 
consecutive monthly decline naito 
the seasonally adjusted surplus in merchandise trade a narrower 
measure came to 458 billion down from 570 billion last 
january and 1006 billion in december naito said it was the 
seventh straight monthly decline in the trade surplus compared to 
its yearearlier level 
imports of aluminum platinum textiles food and crude oil 
increased apparently because of the yens continued rise against 
the us dollar and stronger domestic demand naito said the 
higher yen has raised prices of japanese exports overseas and made 
imports cheaper encouraging japanese to buy more foreign goods 
in 1987s januarymarch quarter the current account surplus 
rose 655 percent from a year earlier on the other hand it 
declined 15 percent in the apriljune quarter yearonyear 132 
percent in the julyseptember quarter and 152 percent in the 
octoberdecember quarter 
exports rose 161 percent in january from a year earlier to 
170 billion compared to 146 billion a year earlier but down 
from the holidayimpacted 228 billion in december 
imports rose 388 percent to 124 billion from 894 billion a 
year earlier 
toshiaki kakimoto chief economist for sumitomo bank ltd said 
januarys unadjusted 161 percent surge in exports was somewhat 
disturbing 
kakimoto said japanese exporters in part had boosted their 
shipments in december and january on fears the yen would rise 
against the dollar and make their products less competitive 
in a separate report the japan automobile importers 
association said imported cars sold in japan reached 8212 autos in 
february up 394 percent from the 5890 sold in the same month 
last year 
