<TEXT>
northwest airlines flew two 
unairworthy jetliners improperly delayed aircraft repairs and 
broke other safety rules the federal aviation administration said 
friday 
the faa made disclosures with the release of 110page report 
detailing a monthlong investigation of the airlines operations 
the report drew no overall conclusion and an faa spokesman at its 
suburban chicago office said the minneapolisbased carrier had a 
very good safety record 
however the faa report said the airline also failed to ensure 
pilots flew no longer than allowed and did not keep proper records 
of repairs classifying some major repairs as minor 
northwest acknowledged in a statement that the faa inspection 
identified 139 findings or areas of concern some of which 
could result in enforcement actions 
of course any finding is of concern to us and as a result 
we have told the faa we will respond completely to each and every 
one of the findings on march 25 said benjamin g griggs jr 
northwests executive vice president of operations 
at least two northwest airlines jetliners both dc10s flew 
several flights between jan 1 and feb 11 in an unairworthy 
condition the report said 
one of the jets flew while missing a small inspection cover 
on top of an engine pylon the report said a second jet flew 
several trips even though the crew failed to neutralize or 
identify the exact cause of a problem with a gauge monitoring the 
speed of an engine turbine 
this is not something that would make an airplane fall out of 
the sky said faa spokesman mort edelstein 
faa authorities studied northwests operations from jan 20 to 
feb 19 as part of an industrywide program of conducting indepth 
inspections of all major airlines edelstein said 
edelstein said the faa would make no decision on whether to fine 
northwest until the airline had a chance to respond and the 
inspection report had been reviewed several times by agency 
officials 
a similar inspection at eastern airlines two years ago led to 
fines totaling 95 million for hundreds of violations mostly 
involving maintenance discrepancies pan am world airways was fined 
195 million in 1986 
despite the safety violations identified at northwest edelstein 
said the airline has a very good safety record they fully 
complied with the safety inspection 
northwest said the findings of the final inspection are likely 
to change after it responds to the faa report which the agency 
said was still being checked for accuracy 
a number of items already have been resolved griggs said 
in our view some of the findings are subject to interpretation 
and we will address these with our faa inspectors 
the faa inspectors found that northwest does not have a system 
to monitor flight and duty time for management pilots to ensure 
compliance with flight time limitations 
in another violation the faa found that the pilot in command of 
northwest flight 49 on feb 10 smoked a cigarette while the no 
smoking light was on 
the inspection also found evidence of deferred maintenance the 
report said for example that a boeing 757 was operated from nov 
1 through jan 7 while having problems with its auxiliary power 
unit repairs on the unit were deferred 13 times before the 
equipment was replaced the report said 
the report found that northwest flight dispatchers were burdened 
with an excessive workload and contended the airline does not 
provide enough qualified dispatchers at each dispatch center to 
ensure proper operational control of each flight 
edelstein and northwest noted that the airline had conducted a 
fivemonth internal audit before the faa inspection began 
the report said northwests own audit could serve as an 
industry model and enabled the faa to conduct a much more 
thorough and comprehensive inspection than would otherwise have 
been possible 
northwest which calls itself the nations fifth largest 
carrier serves 135 cities in 21 countries in asia europe and 
north america the company acquired republic airlines in 1986 and 
has a fleet of 313 aircraft 
</TEXT>
