<TEXT>
shareholders of first city bancorporation of 
texas inc gathered friday to consider chicago banker a robert 
abbouds 15 billion rescue plan that would be the largest 
government bank bailout since 1984 
a twothirds vote of the bankholding companys 37 million 
shares is required to approve the plan which includes nearly 1 
billion in federal assistance a spinoff of poorly performing 
assets and an infusion of privatelyraised capital 
first city which grew quickly during the oil boom to become the 
states fourthlargest bank was hammered by energy and real estate 
loan losses when oil prices plummeted 
for 1987 the company posted a 11 billion loss it has assets 
of 11 billion and operates 59 banks in texas and one in south 
dakota 
abboud an investor seeking to become first citys chairman of 
the board and chief executive officer has promised banking 
regulators to rehabilitate the wobbly company 
in a 200page singlespaced proxy statement sent to 
shareholders abboud said an investor group he heads would raise 
500 million to serve as the primary source of capital for the 
restructured company 
in addition first city subsidiary banks would spin off 179 
billion in book value of nonperforming and other assets to 
collecting bank a new national bank 
in exchange first city would receive about 764 million in 
collecting bank notes and about 970 million in federal deposit 
insurance corp notes 
the fdic pledge is the largest such government rescue since the 
1984 federal bailout of continental illinois bank and trust of 
chicago 
the proxy statement predicted the new company would become 
profitable almost immediately after spinning off the 
poorlyperforming assets 
abboud declined comment until after fridays voting said first 
city spokesman jim day abboud has said he hopes to finalize the 
rescue within weeks of shareholder approval 
under the reorganization plan each 100 shares of first city 
common stock would be exchanged for one common share of the new 
holding company 100 shares of common stock in collecting bank and 
the right to buy more securities in the new company 
the restructuring plan was first announced sept 9 it was 
modified on jan 26 to allow common shareholders and the four 
classes of preferred shareholders to vote as one group 
the first plan had called for each class to vote on the plan 
separately with a rejection from any one group sufficient to 
scuttle the deal 
the earlier arrangement inadvertently provided rancher frederick 
erck a san antonio preferred stockholder potential veto power 
over the deal 
erck a former first city director who resigned in november has 
said he opposes the deal not only because it could hurt him 
financially but because abbouds team would reap too much profit 
from the restructured company 
erck said he did not plan to attend fridays meeting and did 
not disclose how he planned to vote 
