<TEXT>
harcourt brace jovanovich inc said 
thursday its fourthquarter profit climbed more than tenfold from a 
year earlier mostly because of the sale of assets 
harcourt which has interests in publishing insurance and theme 
parks reported a profit of 951 million or 136 a share in the 
three months ended dec 31 1987 compared with earnings of 89 
million or 23 cents a share a year earlier 
revenue for the quarter rose 214 percent to 3276 million from 
2699 million a year earlier 
the company completed the sale of its business periodicals 
trade shows and school supply distribution companies for 334 
million and of two television station for 108 million in the 
quarter 
the latest results included a onetime gain on disposal of assets 
of 1369 million and income from discontinued operations of 1416 
million 
the sales fulfilled the companys asset sale obligation incurred 
when it borrowed to finance a recapitalization last may that helped 
it avoid a hostile takeover bid from british publisher robert 
maxwell 
interest expense in the latest quarter shot up to 785 million 
from 61 million a year earlier and the company said it had a 
loss from continuing operations of 464 million in the latest 
quarter in contrast to a profit of 62 million a year earlier 
for the year harcourt reported net income of 905 million or 
134 a share up from 705 million or 191 a share a year 
earlier 
the decline in per share earnings reflected an increase in the 
average number of shares for the year to 481 million from 37 
million in 1986 
revenue for the year rose to 152 billion from 111 billion a 
year earlier 
